# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: achaemenid-navy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Concentrated at Persepolis, it consisted of an elaborate set of grand festivities that sought to honour the legacy of the Achaemenid Empire, which was founded by Cyrus the Great in 550 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The event was aimed at highlighting ancient Iranian history and also showcasing the country's contemporary advances under Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had been reigning as the Shah of Iran since 1941.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The site brought sixty members of royalty and heads of state from abroad.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] As a result, some accounts have overstated the event's costs and luxuries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The planning for the party took a year, according to the 2016 BBC *Storyville* documentary *Decadence and Downfall: The Shah of Iran's Ultimate Party*.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The filmmakers interviewed people tasked by the Shah to organize the party.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Asadollah Alam, minister of the Royal Court, was named to head the organizing committee.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Cyrus Cylinder appeared in the official logo as the symbol for the event.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] With the decision to hold the main event at the ancient city of Persepolis, near Shiraz, the local infrastructure had to be improved, including the Shiraz International Airport and a highway to Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] While the press and supporting staff would be housed in Shiraz, the main festivities were planned for Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] An elaborate tent city was planned to house attendees.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The area around Persepolis was cleared of snakes and other vermin.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Trees and flowers were planted, and 50,000 song birds were imported from Europe.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Other events were scheduled for Pasargadae, the site of the Tomb of Cyrus, as well as Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Tent City (also called Golden City) was planned by the Parisian interior-design firm of Maison Jansen on 160 acres (0.65 km2).
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] They referred to the meeting between Francis I of France and Henry VIII of England at the Field of the Cloth of Gold in 1520.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Fifty 'tents' (prefabricated luxury apartments with traditional Persian tent-cloth surrounds) were arranged in a star pattern around a central fountain.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Numerous trees were planted around them in the desert, to recreate how ancient Persepolis would have looked.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Each tent was provided with direct telephone and telex connections for attendees to their respective countries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The entire celebration was televised to the world by way of a satellite connection from the site.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The large 'Tent of Honor' was designed for the reception of the dignitaries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The 'Banqueting Hall' was the largest structure, and measured 68 by 24 metres (223 ft × 79 ft).
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tent site was surrounded by gardens of trees and other plants flown in from France and adjacent to the ruins of Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Catering services were provided by Maxim's de Paris, which closed its restaurant in Paris for almost two weeks to provide for the glittering celebrations.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Legendary hotelier Max Blouet came out of retirement to supervise the banquet.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Lanvin designed the uniforms of the Imperial Household.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] 250 red Mercedes-Benz 600 limousines were used to chauffeur guests from the airport and back.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The dinnerware was created using Limoges porcelain and linen by D.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The festivities were opened on 12 October 1971, when the Shah and the Shahbanu paid homage to Cyrus the Great at his mausoleum at Pasargadae.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] For the next two days, the Shah and his wife greeted arriving guests, often directly at Shiraz's airport.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] On 14 October, a grand gala dinner took place in the Banqueting Hall in celebration of the birthday of the Shahbanu.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Sixty members of royal families and heads of state were assembled at the single large serpentine table in the Banqueting Hall.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] They dined off a special dinner service of 10,000 plates commissioned from the English china manufacturer Spode, each plate decorated in turquoise and gold, with the Shah's coat of arms.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The official toast was raised with a Dom Perignon Rosé 1959.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Six hundred guests dined over five and a half hours, thus making for the longest and most lavish official banquet in modern history as recorded in successive editions of the *Guinness Book of World Records*.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] A son et lumière show, the *Polytope of Persepolis* designed by Iannis Xenakis and accompanied by the specially-commissioned electronic music piece *Persepolis*, concluded the evening.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In the evening, a less formal "traditional Persian party" was held in the Banqueting Hall as the concluding event at Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] On the final day, the Shah inaugurated the Shahyad Tower (later renamed the Azadi Tower after the Iranian Revolution) in Tehran to commemorate the event.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tower was also home to the Museum of Persian History.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In it was displayed the Cyrus Cylinder, which the Shah promoted as "the first human rights charter in history".
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The cylinder was also the official symbol of the celebrations, and the Shah's first speech at Cyrus' tomb praised the freedom that it had proclaimed, two and a half millennia previously.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The festivities were concluded with the Shah paying homage to his father, Reza Shah Pahlavi, at his mausoleum.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The event brought together the rulers of two of the three oldest extant monarchies, the Shah and Emperor Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Emperor Hirohito of Japan was represented by his youngest brother, Prince Mikasa.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] By the end of the decade, both the Ethiopian and Iranian monarchies had ceased to exist.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Persepolis was a favoured site for the festivities as it was isolated and thus could be tightly guarded, a very important consideration when many of the world's leaders were gathered there.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Iran's security services, SAVAK, captured and took into "preventive custody" anyone that it suspected of being a potential threat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Ministry of the Court placed the cost at US$17 million (at that time); Ansari, one of the organizers, puts it at US$22 million (at that time).
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The actual figure is difficult to calculate exactly and is a partisan issue.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] *The New York Times* reported several months before the event, "The enormous expense of the celebration is hardly likely to strain the treasury, which is enriched by oil and many other resources.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] According to the BBC documentary *Decadence and Downfall*, the celebrations cost about 120 million United States dollars.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] However, this claim has been described as having no real basis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In addition, the documentary claims the approximately 50,000 birds the Shah imported died within a few days due to the desert climate.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Historian Robert Steele has described this claim as infeasible, arguing that the October climate in Persepolis is more mild than reported and so the birds would have been accustomed to the local weather.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Many accounts from journalists and historians exaggerate cost estimates and claim the regime wanted to spend whatever was necessary.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] However, the Shah only approved the celebration plans after the scope was reduced to one-quarter of the original plan in order to reduce costs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Queen Elizabeth II had been advised not to attend, with security being an issue.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The Duke of Edinburgh and Princess Anne represented her instead.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Other major leaders who did not attend were Richard Nixon and Georges Pompidou.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Nixon had initially planned to attend but later changed his mind and sent Spiro Agnew instead.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Some materials say that the attendee on China’s behalf was Guo Moruo.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] According to his daughter, Guo was originally planned to attend, but he fell ill in transit and then-Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan Zhang Tong attended instead.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Iran's National Film Board produced a documentary of the celebrations, titled *Forugh-e Javidan* (فروغ جاویدان, lit.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] 'Eternal Light') in Persian and *Flames of Persia* in English.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The film was aimed at a Western audience.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Despite a requirement to show the film in 60 cinemas in Tehran, its "overheated rhetoric" and popular resentment at the extravagance of the event meant it did poorly at the domestic box office.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In the *Review of Middle East Studies* in 1980, Ellen-Fairbanks Bodman referred to "a Cecil B.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Only two chadors are in fleeting evidence among the crowds, and the camera prefers girls dancing in tight corduroy pants.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] Persepolis remains a major tourist attraction in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In 2005, reports suggested that the Islamic Republic of Iran intended to reconstruct the tent city created for the 1971 celebration.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] In 2005, it was visited by nearly 35,000 people during the Nowruz holiday.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The tent city continued operating for private and government rent until 1979, when it was looted in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution and the departure of the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The iron rods for the tents and roads built for the festival area still remain and are open to the public, but there are no markers indicating what they were originally for.
[src:achaemenid-navy/2-500-year-celebration-of-the-persian-empire] The dedicated Shahyad Tower remains as a major landmark in Tehran, although it was renamed Azadi Tower in 1979.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The ancient polis is to be distinguished from the municipality, which was named in its honor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The polis lay 17 km east-northeast of the mouth of the Nestos River, almost directly opposite the island of Thasos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] It was a colony placed in previously unsettled Thracian territory, not then a part of Hellas, during the age of Greek colonization.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The city that developed from it became of major importance in ancient Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] After the 4th century AD it declined, contracted to its acropolis, and was abandoned, never to be reoccupied except by archaeologists.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] During the Early Middle Ages, a new settlement emerged near the ancient city.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] It was called Polystylon (Greek: Πολύστυλον), and later considered as the New Abdera (Greek: Νέα Άβδηρα).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] In 2011 the modern municipality of Abdera was synoecized from three previous municipalities comprising a number of modern settlements.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The ancient site remains in it as a ruin.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The municipality of Abdera has 17,610 inhabitants (2021).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The seat of the municipality is the town Genisea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The name *Abdera* is of Phoenician origin and was shared in antiquity by Abdera, Spain and a town near Carthage in North Africa.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] It was variously Hellenized as Ἄβδηρα (*Ábdēra*), Αὔδηρα (*Aúdēra*), Ἄβδαρα (*Ábdara*), Ἄβδηρον (*Ábdēron*), and Ἄβδηρος (*Ábdēros*), before being Latinized as *Abdera*.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Greek legend attributed the name to an eponymous Abderus who fell nearby and was memorialized by Hercules's founding of a city at the location.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The present-day town is written **Avdira** (Άβδηρα) and pronounced [ˈavðira] in modern Greek.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The Phoenicians apparently began the settlement of Abdera at some point before the mid-7th century and the town long maintained Phoenician standards in its coinage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Sapaeans (Ancient Greek, "Σαπαίοι") were a Thracian tribe close to the Greek city of Abdera.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The Greek settlement was begun as a failed colony from Klazomenai, traditionally dated to 654 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] (Evidence in 7th-century-BC Greek pottery tends to support the traditional date but the exact timing remains uncertain.) Herodotus reports that the leader of the colony had been Timesios but, within his generation, the Thracians had expelled the colonists.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Timesios was subsequently honored as a local protective spirit by the later Abderans from Teos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Others recount various legends about this colony.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Strabo describes Abdera as "a Thracian city" at the time of Anacreon and the migration of people from Teos to that area.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The successful colonisation occurred in 544 BC, when the majority of the people of Teos (including the poet Anacreon) migrated to Abdera to escape the Persian invasion of their homeland.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The chief coin type, a *griffon*, is identical with that of Teos; the rich silver coinage is noted for the beauty and variety of its reverse types.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] In 513 and 512 BC, the Persians, under Darius conquered Abdera, by which time the city seems to have become a place of considerable importance, and is mentioned as one of the cities which had the expensive honour of entertaining the great king on his march into Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] In 492 BC, after the Ionian Revolt, the Persians again conquered Abdera, again under Darius I but led by his general Mardonius.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] On his flight after the Battle of Salamis, Xerxes stopped at Abdera and acknowledged the hospitality of its inhabitants by presenting them with a tiara and scimitar of gold.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Thucydides mentions Abdera as the westernmost limit of the Odrysian kingdom when at its height at the beginning of the Peloponnesian War.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] It later became part of the Delian League and fought on the side of Athens in the Peloponnesian War.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Abdera was a wealthy city, the third richest in the League, due to its status as a prime port for trade with the interior of Thrace and the Odrysian kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] In 408 BC, Abdera was reduced under the power of Athens by Thrasybulus, then one of the Athenian generals in that quarter.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] A valuable prize, the city was repeatedly sacked: by the Triballi in 376 BC, Philip II of Macedon in 350 BC; later by Lysimachos of Thrace, the Seleucids, the Ptolemies, and again by the Macedonians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] In 170 BC the Roman armies and those of Eumenes II of Pergamon besieged and sacked it.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The town seems to have declined in importance after the middle of the 4th century BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Cicero ridicules the city as a byword for stupidity in his letters to Atticus, writing of a debate in the Senate, "Here was Abdera, but I wasn't silent" ("Hic, Abdera non tacente me").
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The *Philogelos*, a Greek-language joke book compiled in the 4th century AD, has a chapter dedicated to jokes about Abderans, who are stereotyped as stupid, superstitious, and literal-minded.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Nevertheless, the city counted among its citizens the philosophers Democritus, Protagoras and Anaxarchus, historian and philosopher Hecataeus of Abdera, and the lyric poet Anacreon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Pliny the Elder speaks of Abdera as being in his time a free city.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Abdera had flourished especially in ancient times mainly for two reasons: because of the large area of their territory and their highly strategic position.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The city controlled two great road passages (one of Nestos river and other through the mountains north of Xanthi).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Furthermore, from their ports passed the sea road, which from Troas led to the Thracian and then the Macedonian coast.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The ruins of the town may still be seen on Cape Balastra (40°56'1.02"N 24°58'21.81"E); they cover seven small hills, and extend from an eastern to a western harbor; on the southwestern hills are the remains of the medieval settlement of Polystylon (Greek: Πολύστυλον).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Since the 9th century, Byzantine Polystylon was an episcopal see, under the jurisdiction of the metropolitan bishop of Philippi.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] By the end of the 14th century it fell under the Ottoman rule.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Avdira as a modern administrative unit (community) was established in 1924, and consisted of the villages Avdira, Myrodato (Kalfalar), Pezoula, Giona, Veloni and Mandra, but Myrodato and Mandra became separate communities in 1928.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The municipality Avdira was formed in 1997 by the merger of the former communities Avdira, Mandra, Myrodato and Nea Kessani.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] At the 2011 local government reform it merged with the former municipalities Selero and Vistonida, and the town Genisea became its seat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The municipality has an area of 352.047 km2, the municipal unit 161.958 km2.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The municipal unit Avdira is subdivided into the communities Avdira, Mandra, Myrodato and Nea Kessani.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] The community Avdira consists of the settlements Avdira, Giona, Lefkippos, Pezoula and Skala.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abdera-thrace] Landmarks of Abdera include the Archaeological Museum of Abdera, the Kütüklü Baba Tekke, and Agios Ioannis Beach (also *Paralia Avdiron*) near the village Lefkippos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-navy/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Achaemenid architectural heritage, beginning with the expansion of the empire around 550 B.C., was a period of artistic growth that left an extraordinary architectural legacy ranging from Cyrus the Great's solemn tomb in Pasargadae to the splendid structures of the opulent city of Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] With the advent of the Second Persian Empire, the Sasanian dynasty (224–624) revived Achaemenid tradition by constructing temples dedicated to fire, and monumental palaces.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Perhaps the most striking extant structures to date are the ruins of Persepolis, a once opulent city established by the Achaemenid king, Darius the Great for governmental and ceremonial functions, and also acting as one of the empire's four capitals.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis would take 100 years to complete and would finally be ransacked and burnt by the troops of Alexander the Great in 330 B.C.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Similar architectural infrastructures were also erected at Susa and Ecbatana by Darius the Great, serving similar functions as Persepolis, such as reception of foreign dignitaries and delegates, performance of imperial ceremonies and duties, and also housing the kings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After his death, Cyrus the Great's remains were interred in his capital city of Pasargadae, where today his limestone tomb (built around 540–530) still exists.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The translated ancient accounts give a vivid description of the tomb both geometrically and aesthetically; "With its massive stonework and smooth surfaces relieved by the minimum of decorative detail, the tomb creates an impression of dignity, simplicity, and strength.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In design it combines two distinct elements: a high plinth composed of six receding tiers and a modest, gabled tomb chamber.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In its original state the tomb probably measured c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] 11,1 o m from the once hidden foundation level to the apex of the roof.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Of the six tiers of the plinth, the lowest has an average height of 1,65 m, the second and third have a height of 1,05 m, and the last three each have a uniform height of 57,5 cm.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] 13,35×12,30 m, while the base of the tomb chamber measures c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] As for the cella's other measurements, the narrow doorway, in its present condition without its original doorsills, is 1,39 m high and 78 cm wide; the passage is 1,20 long; and the chamber is 3,17 m in length with a uniform width and height of 2,11 m.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The walls of the chamber are up to 1,50 m thick.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Above the chamber, a hollow compartment in the roof, almost divided in two for structural reasons, measures 4,75 m in length and 85 cm in height.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] There was originally a golden coffin inside the mausoleum, resting on a table with golden supports, inside of which the body of Cyrus the Great was interred.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Upon his resting place, was a covering of tapestry and drapes made from the best available Babylonian materials, using fine Median workmanship; below his bed was a fine red carpet, covering the narrow rectangular base of his tomb.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Translated Greek accounts describe the tomb as having been placed in the fertile Pasargadae gardens, surrounded by trees and ornamental shrubs, with a group of Achaemenian protectors (the "Magi"), stationed nearby to protect the edifice from theft or damage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The magi were a group of on-site Zoroastrian observers, located in their separate but attached structure possibly a caravanserai, paid and cared for by the Achaemenid state (by some accounts they received a salary of daily bread and flour, and one sheep payment a day).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The magi were placed in charge of maintenance and also prevention of theft.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Years later, in the ensuing chaos created by Alexander the Great's invasion of Persia and loss of a centralized authority directing and caring for the Magi, Cyrus the Great's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which the tomb was treated, and questioned the Magi and put them to court.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] On some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more about his attempt to undermine their influence and his show of power in his newly conquered empire, than a concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus of Cassandreia to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The edifice has survived the test of time for some 2,500 years.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After the Arab invasion of Persia and collapse of the Sasanian Empire, Arab armies wanted to destroy this historical artifact, on the basis that it was not in congruence to their Islamic tenets, but quick thinking on the part of the local Persians prevented this disaster.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The Persians renamed the tomb, and presented it to the invading army as the tomb of King Solomon's mother.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] It is likely that the inscription was lost at this time.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Mohammad Reza Pahlavi (Shah of Iran), the last official monarch of Persia, during his 2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire paid significant homage to the Achaemenid kings and specially Cyrus the Great.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Many suspected that, just as Alexander the Great before him, the Shah of Iran wanted to appeal to Cyrus's legacy to legitimize his own rule by extension.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The Shah of Iran, however, was generally interested in protection of Persian imperial historical artifacts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After the Iranian Revolution, the tomb of Cyrus the Great survived the initial chaos and vandalism propagated by the Islamic revolutionary hardliners who equated Persian imperial historical artifacts with the late Shah of Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] There are allegations of the tomb being in danger of damage from the construction of the Sivand Dam on river Polvar (located in the province of Pars) and water related damage, but there is no official acknowledgement of this claim.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] United Nations recognizes the tomb of Cyrus the Great and Pasargadae as a UNESCO World Heritage site.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Perhaps one of the most memorable remaining architectural and artistic works is the bas-relief of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] David Stronach has suggested that there were originally four such figures, set against doorways to the Palace of Cyrus in Pasargadae.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Herodotus, recounts that Cyrus saw in his sleep the oldest son of Hystaspes, [Darius the Great] with wings upon his shoulders, shadowing with the one wing Asia, and with the other wing Europe.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This relief sculpture, in a sense depicts the eclectic inclusion of various art forms by the Achaemenids, yet their ability to create a new synthetic form that is uniquely Persian in style, and heavily dependent on the contributions of their subject states.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After all, that is what distinguishes Achaemenid architecture from those of other kingdoms.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] It is its originality in context of fusion and inclusion of existing styles, in such a way as to create awe-inspiring structures.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis is the Latinized version of the Old Persian name, "Parsa" literally meaning the "city of Persians." Another spectacular achievement of the Achaemenids, Persepolis became one of the four capitals of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis's prestige and grand riches were well known in the ancient world, and it was best described by the Greek historian Diodorus Siculus as "the richest city under the sun".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Today the archaeological remnants of this once opulent city are about 70 kilometers northeast of the modern Iranian city of Shiraz, in the Pars province, in southwestern Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis is a wide, elevated complex 40 feet high, 100 feet wide, and a third of a mile long, composed of multiple halls, corridors, a wide terrace, and a special, double, symmetrical stairway that would provide access to the top of the terrace.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The stairway would delineate relief scenes of various motifs of daily life or nature, including some that were literal as well as metaphorical; Some scenes would show natural acts such as a lion attacking its prey but bear symbolism of spring and the Nowruz festival.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Other scenes would depict, subjects from all states of the empire presenting gifts to the king, as well as scenes depicting royal guards, or scenes of social interactions between the guards or the dignitaries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The most impressive hall in the complex is the Apadana hall, occupying an area of about 109 square meters with 36 Persian columns, each more than 19 m tall.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Each column is fluted, with a square base (except a few in the porticos), and an elaborate capital with two animals supporting the roof.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure was originally closed off from the elements by mud-brick walls over 5 meters thick and over 20 meters tall.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The columns have a composite capital depicting addorsed bulls or creatures.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The columns in the porticoes have circular bases and are capped by ornate capitals after the end of the fluting, themselves topped by detailed addorsed bulls, supporting the roof.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Apadana's relief is also unique in that it delineates the presence and power of the king.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Known as "Treasure reliefs" the depicted scenes on Apadana stress the continuity of the kingdom through Darius the Great, and stress his presence throughout the empire, as well as depict his army of Persian immortals.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Perhaps this was Darius's attempt to create a symbol of the assured continuity of his line.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Apadana hall and the adjacent structures in the complex are believed to have been designed to host large number of people.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In fact, the halls of Persepolis could at any one time host some ten thousand visitors easily, with the king and the royal staff seated appropriately.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis Fortifications (PF) Tablets, dating to between 509 and 494, are ancient Persian documents that describe many aspects of construction and maintenance of the Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The runoff and sewer network of Persepolis are among the most complex in the ancient world.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis is constructed on the foot of a mountain (Rahmat Mountain), with an elevated terrace that is partially man made and partially part of the mountain complex.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] As Persepolis was in essence an important cultural center often used by the beginning of the spring during the festival of Nowruz it enjoyed great precipitation and water runoffs from the molten ice and snow.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The sewer network assumed great importance at this critical time as it was meant to both handle the water flow downward from higher areas as well as manage the inhabitant's sewage runoffs, and their water needs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In order to prevent flooding, the Achaemenids used two engineering techniques to divert snowmelt and mountain runoff.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The first strategy was to collect the runoff in a well with a square opening 4.2 m wide and a depth of 60 m, allowing a volume of 554 cubic meters, or 554,000 liters, (60 x 4.2 x 4.2) of runoff to be collected.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The water would be diverted toward the reservoir via multiple masonry gutters strategically located around the structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The second strategy was to divert water away from the structure should the reservoirs be filled to capacity; this system used a 180-meter-long conduit 7 m wide and 2.6 m deep located just west of the site.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The water system was far more complex than just the reservoirs and the water conduits, and involved a very sophisticated system of closed pipes and irrigation.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The irrigation system was divided into five zones, two serving the north part of the structure and three the southern part.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The irrigation system was designed to be harmonious with the structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Drainage canals were built in the center of the columns, and small draining holes and conduits were included on each floor which would carry water off of the floors, the roof, and the sewage portals into an underground sewage network and away from the structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The five zones (I–V) all possessed a runoff capacity of 260 L/s (liters/second)--more than sufficient for handling mountain runoff, indicating that the system was also used for water supply to the inhabitants, sewage management, and even irrigation of the gardens around the structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In order for such a massive structure to have functioned properly it meant that the weight of the roof, columns and indeed the terrace had to be distributed evenly.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Construction at the base of the mountain offered some structural support.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The ceiling material was a composite application of wood and stone decreasing its overall weight.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Extensive use of stone in Persepolis, not only guaranteed its structural integrity for the duration of its use but also meant that its remains lasted longer than the mud-bricks of Susa palaces.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Scholars agree that it was Darius the Great who initiated the construction and expansion of the Persepolis project, however German archaeologist Ernst E.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Herzfeld, believed that it was Cyrus the Great who chose the site for the construction, although it ultimately came down to Darius the Great to finish the construction and create its impressive buildings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Excavations on behalf of the Oriental Institute of Chicago University, headed by Herzfeld in 1931 and later cooperation by Eric F.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Schmidt in 1933 led to some of the most impressive uncovering of Achaemenid artifacts, palaces, and structures.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Herzfeld felt that the site of Persepolis was made for special ceremonies and was meant to convey the power of the Achaemenid empire to its subject nations.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] On some accounts, Persepolis was never officially finished as its existence was cut short by Alexander the Great, who in a fit of anger, ordered the burning of the city in 330 B.C.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Started originally by Darius the Great a century earlier, the structure was constantly changing, receiving upgrades from subsequent Persian monarchs, and undergoing renovation to maintain its impressive façade.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After the burning of the city, Persepolis was deserted and it was relatively lost to history until the excavations of Herzfeld, Schmidt, and the Chicago team uncovered it in the 1930s.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This great historical artifact is unfortunately at serious risk of "irreparable damage" from neglect, the elements, and vandalism.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Persepolis was by no means the only large scale Achaemenid project, as Susa also hosted a similar structure initiated by Darius for similar ceremonial purposes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] However, that history is able to enjoy the remains of Persepolis as opposed to meager remnants of Susa, owes partly to selection of stone in construction of Persepolis over mud-brick in Susa, and the fact that it had been relatively uninhabited, protecting it from wear and tear of inhabitants.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Politically, Persepolis also was a significant find because nearby discovery of Naqsh-e Rostam, the Persian necropolis home to Darius the Great shed light on the significance it has had as one of the major capitals of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Naqsh-e Rostam would not only house Darius the Great, but also his son Xerxes the Great, Artaxerxes I, and Darius II as well.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The necropolis complex was looted following invasion of Alexander, and possibly in the Sassanid period and during the Arab invasion.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] During the Pahlavi era, the structure enjoyed protection and coverage as Mohammad Reza Shah appeased to its royal and national symbolism.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] During this era many western politicians, poets, artists, and writers were gravitated to Iran, and Persepolis, either as a function of the political relations with the Iranian monarchy or to report on, or visit the ruins.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Such figures include the procession of international dignitaries attending the 2,500 year celebration of the Persian Empire held by Shah, as well as individual visits by such figures as Heinrich Lübke of Germany, and Ralph Graves of *Life* magazine.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Throughout history there have been instances of neglect or vandalism in Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The most notable historical figure to vandalize this structure was Alexander the Great, who after entering Persepolis in 330 B.C. called it the "most hateful city in Asia" and allowed his Macedonian troops to pillage it.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Despite this stern hatred, Alexander also admired the Persians as is obvious through his respect for Cyrus the Great, and his act of giving a dignified burial to Darius III.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Years later upon revisiting the city he had burnt, Alexander would regret his action.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In retrospect, it must be understood that despite his momentary lapse of judgment and his role as having been the single most significant figure to bring an end to Persepolis, Alexander is not by any means the only.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Many individuals in the following centuries would damage Persepolis including thieves and vandals during the Sasanian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] When the Arab armies invaded in the seventh century, they took to causing civil disturbances, religious persecution of Persians, and burning of the books.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] During the Qajar era, and in World War II, the structure would also suffer vandalism at the hands of the Allies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Natural causes such as earthquakes and winds have also contributed to the overall demise of the structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The first French excavation in Susa carried out by the Dieulafoys and the looting and the destruction of Persian antiquities by the so-called archeologists had a deep impact on the site.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Even to date the structure is not safe from destruction and vandalism.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] After the Iranian revolution, a group of fundamentalists serving Khomeini, including his right-hand man Sadegh Khalkhali, tried to bulldoze both the renowned Persian poet, Ferdowsi's tomb, and Persepolis, but they were stopped by the provisional government.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The gallery below highlights only some of these unfortunate acts of vandalism mostly by foreign visitors from the late 1800s to mid-1900s.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] French archaeologist, Egyptologist, and historian Charles Chipiez (1835–1901) has created some of the most advanced virtual drawings of what Persepolis would have looked like as a metropolis of the Persian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The following mini-gallery depicts his virtual recreations.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The first image on the left is a view of the "Talar-i-Takht" or the 100 columns hall of Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Note on the far left portion of the image, the famous "lamassu" (or chimeric man, lion, eagle beast) greeting the visitors (look below for a picture of a lamassu).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Chipiez's drawings delineate his technical prowess and attention to details.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The second picture from the left, is Chipiez's drawing of the columns, their capital ornation, and roof structure of the palace of Darius in Persepolis, also known as "Tachar." It has bull details, as well as the use of wood in construction of the roof.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This explains why the palace caught fire when Alexander the Great, set it aflame.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The third picture from the left, is a more detailed, technical drawing of the "Talar-i-Takht" or the 100 column hall.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Note the layering of the roof, the detailing on the edges of the roof, the window structures, and the technical detailing of the construction poles.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The last picture, on the right, is a panoramic view of the outside of the palace of Darius the Great in Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Details of the Persepolis reliefs are depicted as one can note the symbolic scenes of lions attacking bulls, accompanied by two groups of Persian soldiers protecting (symbolically in this case) the infrastructure above.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Susa was an ancient city (5500 B.C.) even by the time of the Achaemenids.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Susa became a part of the Achaemenid Empire in 539 B.C., and was expanded upon by Darius the Great with construction of Palace of Darius, and later development of palace of Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The palace had a unique Apadana, resembling the one in Persepolis, except this hall was much larger than its Persepolis counterpart covering some 9,200 square meters.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Cyrus the Great chose Susa as a site for one of his fortifications creating a wall there that was significantly taller than older walls made by the Elamites.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This choice might have been to facilitate the trade from Persian Gulf northward.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] What remains in way of structure from this once active capital, are five archaeological mounds, today located in modern Shush, in southwestern Iran, scattered over 250 hectares.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Darius's design of his palace in Susa would resemble Persepolis structurally and aesthetically but would incorporate more of a local flair.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure hosted a large hall of throne or *Apadana* similar to the Apadana of the Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This Susa version of Apadana would be composed of three porticoes at right angles to each other, one of which was closed in all three sides by the walls, and only open in its southward direction.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The palace was decorated with reliefs in enameled terra-cotta of lions walking.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Intricate scenes depicting archers of king Darius would decorate the walls, as well as motifs of nature such as double-bulls, unicorns, fasciae curling into volutes, and palms disposed as a flower or a bell.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The archers in particular depict a unique symbiosis of Persian, Ionian and Greek artistry of the time probably reflecting the origin of the artists who were originally hired by Darius the Great, and their personal reflections on the finished work.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Perhaps the most striking terra-cotta relief is that of the griffin, depicting a winged creature resembling a lion with wings of an eagle (picture not shown here).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The terra-cotta brick reliefs were decorated with lively dye colorations often giving them a lifelike quality.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Architecturally, the palace of Darius in Susa, was the epitome of the Persian architecture at the height of the empire's growth.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Originally erected by Darius, and extensively renovated and modified by Artaxerxes II, it was meant to reflect the same opulence and prestige as Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This was Darius the Great's attempt to decorate his summer capital of Susa and to show case its glory.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] For its construction, Darius brought Egyptian architects and workers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In Darius' palace, Egyptianizing cavetto cornices were introduced as a decoration over the lintels of niches, windows and doorways.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Subsequently, all buildings at Persepolis were to have such cornices.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] French archaeologist Marcel-Auguste Dieulafoy discovered the remnants of the palace of Darius, among the ruins of Susa producing the artifacts of this once magnificent structure now at display in the Louvre museum, France.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] He also wrote a series of architectural observations known as "*L'Art antique de la Perse*" which made a significant impression on the art community as to the intricacy of the Achaemenid architecture.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Although Dieulafoy and his wife Jane, made significant contributions in way of excavation, Susa remains were noted by many observers years before and were in fact officially noted by William K.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Susa was a wealthy city by the time Alexander the Great invaded it, and it is said that he required 10,000 camels and 20,000 donkeys to carry away the treasures.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] For the most part the architectural wealth of Susa lies in its palaces, and ceremonial structures most of which have been eroded away by time or wear and tear.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Today the most important remnants of the Achaemenid contribution to the architecture of ancient Susa are found in remnants of the Palace of Darius the Great in the original excavation site, or hosted in foreign nations' museums as Persian artifacts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Today the archaeological remains of the structure remain exposed to the elements, wear and tear, and human activity, and it seems that remains of Susa would be forever lost, except perhaps for few selected pieces on display at the Louvre or foreign nations' museums.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Below are a few selected photos from the palace of Darius.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The photo on the far left depicts the famous Archers' relief from the palace of Darius, from Susa.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The second picture from the right, is a two-dimensional "lamassu" a mythical creature with wings of an eagle, head of a man, and body of a lion.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Naqsh-e Rostam is an archaeological site located about 6 kilometers northwest of Persepolis in the Marvdasht region of Fars province, Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Nash-e Rostam acts as a necropolis for the Achaemenid kings, but is a significant historical entity in that it also housed ancient Elamite relief, as well as later relief by the Sasanian kings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Naqsh-e Rostam is not the actual name of this massive structure, but is the New Persian compound word composed of "Naqsh" meaning "face", or "facade", and "Rostam" referring to the hero of the Persian epic Shahnameh.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The Elamites, Achaemenids, and Sasanians lived centuries before the drafting of the Shahnameh by the Persian poet Ferdowsi, and therefore the name is a misnomer, the result of the great amnesia of Persians about their ancient past, that settled over them after being conquered by the Arabs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The name therefore is a retrospective creation, due to lack of historical documents and lack of any inclusive knowledge of its origin.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In ancient Persia, this structure would overlook the now long gone city of Istakhr easily accessible from Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Istakhr had a religious role as it was the place where Achaemenids held their reverence of the water goddess Anahita.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure is carved into a native limestone rock mountain, and houses the burial chambers of Darius the Great, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I, and Darius II, all Achaemenid monarchs of Persia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] There is also an incomplete tomb, as only its lower cruciform arm is carved out of the rock, while the rest is unfinished.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] It is speculated to belong to king Darius III.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The kings were interred behind a facade and rock relief, that would resemble an accurate depiction of the king's own palace and its structural details.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The tombs are carved into the mountain's side, in form of a cross (Old Persian: *chalipa*), depressed into the mountain's limestone background, and elevated from the ground.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The relief which is found in the depressed cruciform is that which depicts the respective king's palace, and also depicts on its roof, the relief figure of the king praying, to Ahura Mazda or what most believe is a reference to the Zoroastrian icon, Faravahar.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure is cubical in base, with blind impressions on the side resembling windows, and a ruined staircase leading to a small door in the front leading to a completely empty interior.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] There are varied speculations as to its function discussed below.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure also once housed an ancient Elamite relief which has been almost entirely replaced by the Sasanian reliefs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Today only a figure of a man remains of the Elamite contribution to this mountain.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The later Sasanians, also created their own historical signature on the structure, called the Naqsh-e Rajab.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Though numerous and very detailed, the study of the Sasanian architecture achievements sheds light on some of the architectural achievements during the second Persian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The staircase leads to a small door (5 feet by 6 feet in dimensions) opening to an interior apartment of about 12 feet square.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The structure's roof houses a minimal entablature of a repeating square pattern.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The entire structure is posited on a raised stone platform that is composed of a few stone slabs, in a sequentially smaller yet in a concentric, pyramidally shaped succession.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This structure is enigmatic, both in its aesthetic choice seen in its rather odd design, and façade, as well as its location, and supposed function.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] This would certainly be logical as the city was also adjacent to Istakhr, a major religious and cultural center.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The concept of the temple being used as a fire sanctuary, is however not likely because there is no general ventilation for smoke and gasses, and also that it differs so drastically, architecturally and aesthetically from other well known contemporary temple sites in Pars.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Curiously the design although unique, is not the only one of its kind.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The name "Prison of Solomon" is of course a misnomer since Solomon never did erect this structure.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Just like the "Cube of Zoroaster", the function of the "Solomon's prison" is not well understood.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] There are theories about the structures being used as a depository of objects of dynastic or religious importance as well as theories of it being a temple of fire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] It should also be noted, that the structures as they exist today are not simply the work of the Achaemenid architects and have been modified, and improved by the Sasanians, who also used them for their festive, and political needs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Carved high in Mount Behistun of Kermanshah, one can find the Behistun inscription, a text etched into the stone of the mountain describing the manner in which Darius became the king of Persia, after the previous ruler (Cambyses II), and how he overthrew the magus usurper of the throne.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In this inscription Darius also details his satraps and delineates his position as the king and emperor of the Persian empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] Architecturally speaking, the Behistun inscription is a massive project, that entailed cutting into the rough edge of the mountain in order to create bas-relief figures as seen in the pictures above.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The Behistun mountain, rises up to some 1700 feet as part of the Zagros mountain chains in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The mountain's location is ideal being close to both Ecbatana and Babylonia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The bas-relief itself is located some 300 feet above the base of the mountain.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The figures represent two of the king's soldiers, the king himself standing over a fallen usurper and captives of several nations possibly dissidents, or co-conspirators.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The inscription itself is written in cuneiform character in Old Persian, Babylonian, and Median.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] The inscription is interpreted and deciphered with the help of many intellectuals and scholars, but the Orientalist Sir Henry Rawlinson is credited as being most critical in the process of deciphering the piece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p01] In this sense, the Behistun inscription is not only a significant architectural work, but also a significant linguistic tool, as important to the old world understanding of ancient Persia and its languages, as Rosetta Stone is to understanding ancient Egypt and its languages.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p02] Elements of the Achaemenid style can be seen in contemporary Iranian architecture.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-architecture-p02] Buildings built by the Pahlavi dynasty, in particular, show extensive influence of Achaemenid architecture and art.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The **Achaemenid navy** (Old Persian: 𐎴𐎠𐎺 *nāva*) was the principal naval force of the Achaemenid Empire which existed between 525 BC and 330 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] In Old Persian, the written language of Achaemenid inscriptions, the word used to refer to the 'navy' or 'fleet' was "*nāva*", a noun in plural feminine nominative form.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] It is of the same root of Indo-European for words such as "navy" and "navigate".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] In modern usage of Persian language, the word has retained its form and meaning (lit.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] No relevant primary documents have been found about it, nor have any ruins of Persian naval installations or remains of ships been excavated.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] While independent Persian tradition is lost, all we know about the Achaemenid navy is recorded by ancient Greek historians like Herodotus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Scholars categorize the record of operation of the navy to two distinct periods from 525 to 479, and from 479 to 330 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Cambyses founded the navy for conquest of Egypt in the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] After him, Darius I deployed the navy to strengthen dominance over the coast of Asia Minor, as well as its adjacent islands.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] During reign of Darius, Persians captured Samos (c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] 517 BC), conquered Thrace, waged war on Scythia (c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] 512 BC), and suppressed rebellions started in 500 BC, leading to the Battle of Lade (494 BC).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The navy had lost its presence in the Aegean Sea, and its strength was reduced.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] 468 BC), the Persians were defeated and lost 200 ships according to the account of Thucydides.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The next significant defeat occurred in c.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] 450 BC, when they lost a war in Cyprus (near modern-day Larnaca).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The creation the organization, infrastructure, and financial basis of the Achaemenid navy is attributed to Darius I.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The coasts of Phoenicia, as well as Cyprus and Cilicia, always played a strategic role in the Achaemenid navy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Strabo and Herodotus mentioned two central bases for the navy: one in Cilicia and the other in Kyme–Phocaea (both located in modern-day Turkey).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Centers that trained crew for vessels were isolated from the central bases.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Cilician base was heavily guarded by a large number of troops, whose payments were financed by the local tributes in that satrapy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] It is likely that Acco served as the third main base.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] According to Kaveh Farrokh, the first naval headquarters that hosted high command of the navy was located along the Shatt al-Arab, where it leads to the Persian Gulf (located in the modern-day Khuzestan Province of Iran).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] However, Cilicia was the main base and was always ready for deployment because unlike Shatt al-Arab, it was intended for power projection.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Smaller squadrons were stationed elsewhere, like those of Sidon and Halicarnassus, as well as Samos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] An important base was a shipyard located at Tripolis, where Lebanese timber were nearby.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Nile valley also served as a strategic base of operation, when Egypt was a satrapy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid settlements like Bahrain, Oman, Yemen and the Indian subcontinent were regular destinations for naval ships.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] It is thought likely that bases existed in Abdera and Myus, though this is uncertain.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces had an active presence in the Black Sea, the Aegean Sea, the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf among others.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] They operated patrols in river or littoral environments like Shatt al-Arab and Euphrates in Mesopotamia, Nile in Egypt and Sind in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The command hierarchy of the navy is not certain, but Greek sources indicate that high commanders were selected from the imperial aristocracy.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] There are reports of commanders of ships, and commanding officers of fleets with various non-Persians backgrounds, such as those of Carians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Commanders of Greek origin are also reported to have served in the navy, including even one Athenian.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Almost nothing is known about sailors of lower rank.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] In the wake of creating the navy, Persians hired Phoenician rowers and sailors, but later recruited from other subject peoples.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The marines standing in the forces were either Persians, Medes, or Scythians.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The servicemen were probably employed with full payment, because lengthy deployments imposed a drastic change to their communities especially if it included one or two harvests.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The first Achaemenid naval vessels, which were built at Phoenician shipyards, measured 40 meters (130 ft) in length and 6 meters (20 ft) width, and were capable of carrying 300 troops at best.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] According to Christopher Tuplin, Cypriot ships "appear a significant element in Persian fleets on various occasions".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Persians were the first nation to use triremes in significant numbers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The first large trireme was commissioned by Cambyses.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] By 490 BC, the backbone of the fleet was consisted of triremes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Some triremes were modified as troopers, as well as some for carrying horses and supplies or building bridges.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Persian triremes differed from those of the Greek, and used Phoenician design.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The third level of rowers in Greek vessels was accommodated by adding a outrigger, but the Persians added to the height of the compartment instead.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] They reportedly were 110 feet (34 m) to 120 feet (37 m) long and had a beam of 15 feet (4.6 m).
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The ships were most likely capable of reaching 12 knots (22 km/h) under good sailing conditions.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] They could reach full speed in 30 seconds from a dead stop.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Equipped with one mast with square sail, the triremes had rudders made up of two bladed oars, one on each side of stern, united by a crossbar.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The ram was made out of bronze, and was long and tapered to a single point.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The metal rams were designed to slice into the hulls of enemy ships after an impact.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Equipment included grappling hooks (used to catch and halt enemy ships) and two mangonels, the latter throwing stones or flammable projectiles.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] A typical Persian trireme is reported to have had 170 rowers, with the upper file carrying 62, and the middle and lower files each 54.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] In addition to the rowers, other personnel aboard triremes included 14 marines and some spare rowers and oars in case they were needed.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] In 480 BC, each trireme carried 200 men and 30 marines, according to Herodotus.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Triremes were too crowded to store their own supplies, and relied on support vessels for food and water.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] It was normal for the crew to disembark in the evening for eating and sleep.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid navy later used more advanced vessels like quinqueremes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Other types of vessel in the fleet were triaconters, penteconters and light boats.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Smaller vessels used for river patrols could carry a maximum of 100–200 troops.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The navy operated a large number of vessels used to carry food and other supplies, which commonly had a displacement of 100 to 150 tons, at the time they invaded Egypt in 373 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Ships capable of carrying 350 to 500 tons were also used in significant numbers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] They also had horse transporters (*hippagogoi*) specifically built for this purpose, that could easily carry 30 horses.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Persian horse transport ships were good sailing ships that took advantage of the favorable winds, according to Anthony J.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Papalas, who adds they were probably designed to match the speed of a trireme.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] It is probable that horse transports were galleys with a shallow draft, that allowed horses get off in the waters and embark via a ramp.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenids are known to have used vessels for connecting the banks of rivers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The bridges were built by joining vessels to one another and lashing them together, to erect a roadway with planks.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon reports such bridges, one made using 37 boats on Tigris, and another using seven on Maeander.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] During its early years under Cambyses, the Achaemenid navy is assumed to possess about 300 triremes, which was equal to the sum of the fleet of Egypt and its ally Polycrates of Samos.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] This number was later doubled, with 600 triremes mentioned in 494 and 490 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The initial set-up of the navy (300 triremes) may have had up to 51,000 rowers and thousands of sailors and marines.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The original number of vessels in the fleet was eventually quadrupled, according to Greek sources.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus' account of naval forces under Xerxes I, put the number of warships in service at 1,207, in addition to 3,000 transport ships.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Contemporary academic estimates range from 500 to 1,000 vessels, according to Matt Waters.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Scholars maintain that this number included large numbers of reserve ships, and the navy had not enough full oar crews to operate them all.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus also states that Persians arrived for the Battle of Marathon (490 BC) with 600 triremes and some horse transport vessels.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Though the number is rejected by some academics, Anthony J.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Papalas states that evidence does support this report.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Considering that each ship had an average of 50 oarsmen (the absolute minimum for a trireme) and 10 to 20 seamen and marines were also aboard, the navy compromised 36,000 to 42,000 men, at least.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] After the Battle of Salamis (480 BC), the fleet began to decline and never regained its peak numbers.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The largest figure estimated after 404 BC is 400 triremes.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The number was still equal to, if not more than, the fleets of the Athenian alliance.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon wrote in *Anabasis*, "his (Cyrus the Younger) ensign was a golden eagle with outspread wings mounted upon a long shaft and this continues even unto this day as the ensign of the Persian king".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] While there is not much to confirm this, some scholars maintain that *Alexander Mosaic* contained a depiction of the standard (on the part which is now damaged), head of a bird in yellow on a red cloth.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] There is also a square plaque found at Apadana in plain, and it is quite possible that it shows the eagle.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenid navy was the first true "imperial navy" that appeared in history.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] Persians are also credited for establishing the 'trireme navy' as the naval standard of their time.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The establishment of the Achaemenid navy set the basis of Iranian naval engineering, as well as "a powerful Persian maritime tradition that remained in the region until the arrival of the British East India Company and the Royal Navy by the mid-19th century AD".
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces affected the coastal subjects of the Achaemenid Empire to a great extent.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] They were put under much tighter control from the capital, and were heavily involved in military campaigns of the Achaemenids.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-navy] The Sidonians profited financially from the naval base stationed in their city.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-persian-lion-rhyton] The **Achaemenid Persian Lion Rhyton** (Persian: تکوک شیر غران) is a gold rhyton from the Achaemenid Empire, dated to about 500 BC.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-persian-lion-rhyton] It is 6.7 inches high (about 17 cm.) and is made in solid gold, with the different parts joined together by soldering, done so skilfully as to leave no obvious marks.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-persian-lion-rhyton] It was excavated in diggings sponsored by the Fletcher Fund in 1954 in southwest Persia and is now in the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City, United States.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-persian-lion-rhyton] A rhyton is a kind of cup or drinking vessel which normally terminates in the shape of an animal's head or horns, common in the Near East and ancient Greece.
[src:achaemenid-navy/achaemenid-persian-lion-rhyton] Early Iranians used rhyta with an animal head at the end of the vessel; later in the Achaemenid period the animal part of the rhyton was usually located in front of it and at a 90-degree angle to the vessel.
